Alongside `modifyindex!`, `swapindex!` and `replaceindex!` I've also implemented
* `getindex_atomic(::GenericMemory, i, ...)`
* `setindex_atomic!(::GenericMemory, i, ...)` and
* `setindexonce_atomic!(::GenericMemory, i, ...)`.

I added some converts `(val isa T ? val : convert(T, val)::T)` those `*index` methods and the support for indexing in `@atomic` macro with the following semantics:
```julia
@macroexpand (@atomic a[1])
:(Base.getindex_atomic(a, 1, :sequentially_consistent))

@macroexpand (@atomic order a[1])
:(Base.getindex_atomic(a, 1, order))

@macroexpand (@atomic a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.setindex_atomic!(a, 1, 2.0, :sequentially_consistent))

@macroexpand (@atomic order a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.setindex_atomic!(a, 1, 2.0, order))

@macroexpand (@atomicswap a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.swapindex!(a, 1, 2.0, :sequentially_consistent))

@macroexpand (@atomicswap order a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.swapindex!(a, 1, 2.0, order))

@macroexpand (@atomic a[1] += 2.0)
:((Base.modifyindex!(a, 1, +, 2.0, :sequentially_consistent))[2])

@macroexpand (@atomic order a[1] += 2.0)
:((Base.modifyindex!(a, 1, +, 2.0, order))[2])

@macroexpand (@atomiconce a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.setindexonce_atomic!(a, 1, 2.0, :sequentially_consistent, :sequentially_consistent))

@macroexpand (@atomiconce o1 o2 a[1] = 2.0)
:(Base.setindexonce_atomic!(a, 1, 2.0, o1, o2))

@macroexpand (@atomicreplace a[1] (2.0=>3.0))
:(Base.replaceindex!(a, 1, 2.0, 3.0, :sequentially_consistent, :sequentially_consistent))

@macroexpand (@atomicreplace o1 o2 a[1] (2.0=>3.0))
:(Base.replaceindex!(a, 1, 2.0, 3.0, o1, o2))
```

Please have a look and comment!

